# A Bicycle Computer in Several Parts

For any cyclist who passes a certain point (maybe just beyond casual, but then all the way up to professional), getting statistics about how you ride, and being able to see where your route is going, become important parts of your journey.

Most cyclists would therefore invest in a cycling computer. I myself ride with a [Garmin Edge 520](https://buy.garmin.com/en-GB/GB/p/166370), a very capable device that has seen me through many thousands of miles of commuting, riding, racing, and touring.

![Garmin Edge 520](https://static.garmincdn.com/en/products/010-01368-00/g/sc-01-lg.jpg)

These devices tend to have quite a lot of features:
- GPS / GLONASS positioning
- Maps and route navigation
- Speed, altitude, direction readouts
- Ride recording
- A decent battery life
- Waterproofing
To name but a few...

So, back in 2014, I decided to see just how easy it would be to build one for myself, using off the shelf components as much as I can.

**TL;DR**

It's _very_ difficult! I have massive respect for the engineers and designers who design and build these things for a living and do it so well in such a compact form factor!

## Hardware
Let's start off with the hardware, as that is the bit that you can actually see. My initial thoughts were, it's not too difficult, right? I'd just started playing with [Arduino](https://www.arduino.cc/)s, and had a spare [Arduino Mega 2560](https://store.arduino.cc/arduino-mega-2560-rev3) to play around with (though a previous revision to this one).

### The Controller
The Arduino Mega is a pretty powerful board for a microcontroller. It's based on the ATmega2560, and has 54 digital I/O pins (16 of which are Pulse Width Modulating pins), 16 analog inputs and 4 serial ports. The ATmega2560 chip itself provides 256KB of flash ROM and 8KB of RAM to work with, which is a lot for a small microcontroller!

### Features
Now I had my base controller, it was time to see what I could add to it to get my functionality. Eventually I settled on
- A GPS Shield, like [this one from Adafruit](https://www.adafruit.com/product/1272),
- A 10 degrees of Freedom board, like [this one from SparkFun](https://www.sparkfun.com/products/13995)
- A TFT touch screen display, like [this one from Adafruit](https://www.adafruit.com/product/1770)

What does all this give me?
- The GPS shield lets me know 
  - where I am 
  - what speed I'm travelling at
  - what direction I'm going in
  - my approximate altitude
  - Date and Time
- The 10 Degrees of Freedom (DoF) board tells me
  - Accelerometers to tell me how fast I am accelerating
  - Magnetometer
  - Gyroscope
  - Pressure sensor (more accurate altitude)
  - Temperature
  - Compass
- The TFT touch screen
  - Lets me do basic IO

### Prototyping
The first version of the device was constructed out of recycled wire, on a prototyping board, on top of a chair in the garden! It really wasn't anything fancy, but when I first saw data on my laptop over the serial connection, it was amazing. Here I was, a hobby developer, getting data about the world from a device I had constructed! It was euphoric!

To start off with, I used a 20x4 LCD display, and some old CAT5 network cable that I had laying around, with a protying board

![prototype hello world board](data:image/png;base64,)

It wasn't pretty, but it worked!

Once I understood the basics of how to build a circuit that would work with the device, I moved on to getting data from the GPS shield and the 10DOF board.

![prototype degrees of freedom on a touch screen](data:image/png;base64,)

The board itself is tiny, but here you can eee an example of me translating the roll into a line on the TFT screen (along with some artifacts left over from drawing outside the area I'm clearing), along with some data from the GPS shield.

The [Arduino IDE](https://arduino-ide.en.softonic.com/) was the base for all the software that I wrote for the project. It is a simple IDE, really not much more than a text editor and a way of communicating with the arduino itself. But it does the job, and let me experiment on the device and the results.

### Software
Once I had an understanding of the hardware and it's capabilities, I wanted to experiment with what it was possible to do with the software. I had a 320x240px touch screen, and could draw on it, detect touch points on it, and display whatever I wanted ultimately.
This was the challenging part. It turns out that I can come up with all sorts of fancy User Experiences for the data, but actually assembling it, that is challenging.

**What makes it challenging?**

Well, the hardware itself really. The arduino device doesn't have a dedicated graphics processor library, so you have to draw every primitive element by hand. That's already hard. Couple that with the limitations of memory on the device. Now you start getting into fancy tricks to optimise memory usage, like using different data types instead of `int`s, bitshifting, avoiding strings. This is the very opposite of how I am used to working!

Ultimately the code for this project never made it beyond this prototype, though the [Github Repository](https://github.com/dlpb/cycle-computer) is there for you to peruse, as are the libraries I used to write the software ([ADXL362](https://github.com/dlpb/ADXL362), [Arduino GFX](https://github.com/dlpb/arduino-gfx)).


### Assembly
All of these are pretty easy to get your hands on and prototype with on a prototyping board, but then I wanted to put them together onto a circuit board. So for that, I used a custom PCB service from [Fritzing](https://fritzing.org/) to print my circuit board. Really this just held it all together.

### Final version
The final version worked. For some definition of work. I had a device that would display data on the screen. There was some basic interaction going on. I could use it. 
However, it was restricted to being tethered to my laptop. It didn't have an external battery (and I wasn't going to go down that path). It didn't have a fancy UX. The interface was fancy, but slow. 

![various components](data:image/png;base64,)

In the end, it all came together with a few shields and a custom circuit board (top right). It worked, though I never got it mounted to my bike so I never took it too it's full potential in that respect.

### Conclusion
It was a fun project to build. I'm glad I did. I learnt a lot about hardware, and embedded programming. It was the groundwork for a lot of my future projects. But it was difficult to make a success of it. I'm glad I have my dedicated cycling computer! And I have a massive respect for the engineers that designed and built it!
